Rating: 3
Made the recipe as given (using shitake, oyster & baby bella mushrooms) except for the time. It took several hours to reduce the liquid to the consistency I wanted. The extended time greatly improved the texture and taste of the dish. Took it to a New Year's Eve supper to go with steak, baked potatoes & salad. Very easy. Very tasty. I will make it again.

Rating: 3
I used beer in place of wine. It definately needs more flour, it didn't thicken with only 1 tablespoon of flour. I also added a few sprigs of rosemary because it definitely needs some herbs besides parsley. I made these the night before a potluck and put them in a crockpot and the flavor got even better the next afternoon.

Rating: 4
This was a great dish, I made this and served them with ribeye roast and mashed potatoes. I double the recipe since I was cooking for 30 people. They raved this more that the meat. I did not have vegetable broth so I used chicken broth and I used 2 1/2 tablespoons of flour since there was definately a lot of liquid. It took me almost 2 hours to reduce it, but this is by far the best mushroom gravy.

Rating: 4
A lovely companion for most meats; easy to prepare and sophisticated. I used 4 different kinds of fresh mushrooms and cut them into chunks. The recipe does not specify whether to leave them whole or cut up. I would add an extra tablespoon (or 2) of flour however, as there is a good deal of cooking liquid involved. This would be a nice buffet dish as well.

Rating: 4
I served this with really good prime rib, and the mushrooms got more comments than the beef. Delicious, and the gravy is a wonderful compliment to beef. I didn't make any changes, the recipe didn't require any. So easy and so good.

